<text top="520" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t8" reading_order_no="97" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">The German Health Survey of 1999 used the CIDI and</text>
<text top="531" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t9" reading_order_no="98" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">DSM IV to identify 'cases' in a realised sample of 4,181.<a href="">ers [25]</a>.</text>
<text top="543" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t10" reading_order_no="99" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">Data for 12-month prevalence of 'any mood disorder' and<i><b>The National German Health Survey, 1999</b></i></text>
<text top="555" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t11" reading_order_no="100" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">'any anxiety disorder', relating fairly closely to the 'com-</text>
<text top="567" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t12" reading_order_no="101" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">mon mental disorders' are available [11,12]. Prevalence</text>
<text top="578" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t13" reading_order_no="102" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">rates are very similar to similar surveys elsewhere. 12-</text>
<text top="590" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t14" reading_order_no="103" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">month prevalence was analysed for level of school</text>
<text top="602" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t15" reading_order_no="104" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">achievement, employment, and an index of 'social class'<a href="">s' are available [11,12]. Pre</a>valence</text>
<text top="614" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t16" reading_order_no="105" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">combining education, income and job status. In each case</text>
<text top="625" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t17" reading_order_no="106" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">high prevalences were found in the more disadvantaged</text>
<text top="637" left="55" width="70" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t18" reading_order_no="107" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">groups (Table 4)</text>
<text top="661" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t19" reading_order_no="108" segment_no="12" tag_type="text">People with Abitur level education had less illness, just</text>
<text top="672" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t20" reading_order_no="109" segment_no="12" tag_type="text">significant at the 0.05 level. The unemployed had signifi-</text>
<text top="684" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t21" reading_order_no="110" segment_no="12" tag_type="text">cantly more illness than the full-time employed. People in<a href=""> 4)</a></text>
<text top="696" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t22" reading_order_no="111" segment_no="12" tag_type="text">medium and high class groups had significantly less ill-</text>
<text top="708" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t23" reading_order_no="112" segment_no="12" tag_type="text">ness than those in the low class group (this indicator</text>
<text top="719" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t24" reading_order_no="113" segment_no="12" tag_type="text">incorporates education and income with occupation).</text>
<text top="473" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t25" reading_order_no="114" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">These results harmonise closely with the overall results of</text>
<text top="484" left="313" width="170" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t26" reading_order_no="115" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">the Inequalities Review described above.</text>
<text top="508" left="313" width="222" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t27" reading_order_no="116" segment_no="7" tag_type="title">Summary of the six major European studies (Table 5)</text>
